<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope-Mozambique Bjt   09-11 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Mozambique, Bjt,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope's Visit To Marxist Mozambique Comes Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note pope visits Sept. 16-19.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II's customary message
of peace and reconciliation could be a controversial one when he
visits Mozambique, a southern African nation wracked by 12 years of
civil war, drought and systematic destruction of public facilities.
   A newsletter issued last year by Frelimo, the governing Marxist
party, called the former Portuguese colony's Roman Catholic bishops
``enemies of the people'' after they suggested the government meet
with guerrillas of the Mozambican National Resistance.
   But Cardinal Alexandre dos Santos says he hopes the pope will
call for reconciliation when he visits the country Sept. 16-19.
   President Joaquim Chissano, who was visiting the pope in the
Vatican when the bishops made their plea, said it was impossible to
negotiate with the guerrillas who, he charged, mutilate children,
burn schools and hospitals, and massacre villagers.
   The guerrilla movement, known as RENAMO, denies such charges and
says it is fighting to replace the Marxist government with a
democratic one.
   ``We hope (the pope) will say something about peace since we are
in this situation of war,'' said Dos Santos, who became a cardinal
in June. ``We don't see how we can end this struggle without
reconciliation. ... It is necessary to have dialogue with these
people.''
   Foreign Minister Pascoal Mocumbi said the government hopes the
pope will not appeal for negotiations with RENAMO. He said no one
had the right to suggest that the government ``should talk with
terrorists, with those who commit massacres, ... those who have
been roundly condemned, not only by Mozambique but by the
international community.''
   Job Chambal, director of the government's Department of
Religious Affairs, is overseeing the return of some church property
confiscated when Frelimo came to power at independence from
Portugal in 1975.
   He said of the bishops: ``Our quarrel with them is not the fact
that they called for negotiations _ any Mozambican is free to think
that. The one thing that worried the government was to ... say that
the government as well as RENAMO are responsible for the war.''
   Chambal said the plan to return all confiscated church property
used for worship came coincidentally three months before the pope's
visit.
   ``We were not trying to please the pope,'' he said. ``It's a way
of showing we don't belong to an evil empire.''
   Since 1982, when the late President Samora Machel held meetings
with church leaders, the government has sought to ease tension
between the churches and Frelimo.
   The government invited the pope to visit Mozambique in his
capacity as head of the Vatican state, and it is sharing expenses
with the local church.
   ``It's very expensive, but it's very important,'' Chambal said.
``The willingness of the pope to come to Mozambique means there's
been a very big improvement because people have understood what it
means when we say we have a socialist state.''
   ``We are Marxists, but all of us in government have some
religious background,'' said Chambal, who was reared a
Presbyterian. ``We still have some religious feeling. Even our
revolutionary songs have a religious taste. But our children will
be more Marxist, and teach their children to be Marxists.''
   He said the government wants children to be influenced only by
the state until they are 18, when they can choose whether to go to
church, but this policy is not enforced. In the years immediately
after independence, some churches were closed, services were
interrupted and religious activity was officially discouraged.
   Now churches operate freely. Both cathedral services and prayer
meetings in the bush are packed on Sundays.
   The Frelimo revolutionaries accused Roman Catholic bishops and
priests of cooperating with the Portuguese colonial government and
opposing independence in return for a favored position as a state
church.
   The cardinal says some Portuguese clergymen supported
colonialism, but denies the Mozambican Roman Catholic Church as a
whole was against independence.
   All church-state problems are not resolved, Cardinal dos Santos
said, but he maintained the government does not understand the
church's goals.
   ``They suppose we want only to teach those who want to be
religious leaders,'' he said. ``We also want to prepare the people
for running the country.''
   Dos Santos said that of Mozambique's 14.5 million people, 2
million are Catholics.
</TEXT>
