<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Florence 3rdLd-Writethru a0629 09-11 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florence, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0629,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead; Minimal Property Damage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 4th graf ```All we..' to UPDATE with
Gilbert upgraded to hurricane, deletes outdated 19th and 20nd
grafs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NU1, NU2, NU3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remnants of Hurricane Florence pushed
inland Saturday as thousands of Gulf Coast residents returned home,
happy to find little damage from 80 mph winds and sheets of rain.
   ``I was expecting to see my little trailer gone. It isn't tied
down or anything,'' Bill Gibson, 58, said as he hauled away a
12-foot-long branch that had fallen from a tree next to his
undamaged trailer house in Venice, near the mouth of the
Mississippi River.
   One death _ that of an Alabama man who drowned Friday trying to
secure a boat against the rising winds _ was linked to the storm,
which was downgraded to a tropical depression by dawn Saturday.
   ``All we lost was a good night's sleep,'' said Wade Guice, civil
defense director for Harrison County, Miss. ``This storm fizzled
out. The hurricane didn't come.''
   Meanwhile, Tropical Storm Gilbert formed in the eastern
Caribbean and strengthened into a hurricane Saturday night. The
National Hurricane Center reported its position late Saturday night
as near latitude 16.0 north, longitude 67.3 west, about 225 miles
southeast of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
   Maximum sustained winds were estimated to be nearly 75 mph.
Gilbert was expected drop 5 to 10 inches of rain on Puerto Rico and
the Dominican Republic by Sunday, the hurricane center said.
   Florence hit on the 23rd anniversary of Hurricane Betsy's 1965
landfall but packed little of Betsy's punch. Betsy killed more than
70 people in Louisiana and did an estimated $1.1 billion in damage.
   Damage estimates for Florence were unavailable but appeared to
be relatively minor.
   Crews from the Louisiana Office of Emergency Preparedness went
out Saturday to assess the damage and start cleaning up, said state
police Trooper Paul Wood.
   Sheriff's deputies said property damage appeared to be minimal
and limited mainly to downed power lines that knocked out
electricity to 115,000 or more homes and businesses.
   Thousands of people ordered to leave homes in nine parishes
Friday returned home when Florence dropped from hurricane to
tropical storm. They found several broken branches and a few bent
or broken signs.
   ``We were expecting the worst and hoping for the best, and we
got the best out of it,'' said Larry Ciko, a spokesman for the
sheriff's office in St. Tammany Parish, across Lake Pontchartrain
from New Orleans.
   A tornado was reported in neighboring Tangipahoa Parish. The
National Weather Service said the tropical depression was pushing a
wide band of showers and thunderstorms into northeast Louisiana,
extreme southwest Arkansas and central Mississippi.
   At 5 p.m. CDT, the National Weather Service said Florence was
centered over central Louisiana, moving toward the west-northwest
and weakening.
   Winds unleashed by Florence never reached the 100 mph that had
been feared.
   Bill Tregre, a spokesman for the two companies that supply
electricity to most of south Louisiana, said the storm cut power to
about 70,000 Louisiana Power & Light Co. customers and about 33,000
customers of New Orleans Public Service Inc. About 6,900 remained
without power Saturday afternoon, but Tregre said he expected all
would have their electricity restored before Sunday.
   Ciko said Central Louisiana Electric Co. officials told him that
12,000 to 14,000 customers were without power at the height of the
storm.
   Although the storm was expected to bring 5 to 10 inches of rain,
less than 2 inches was reported around most of southeast Louisiana.
   ``The fast movement of the storm kept a lid on the rains,'' said
a weather service meteorologist who refused to give his name.
   Florence, the sixth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic storm
season, was the second hurricane. The first, Debby, reached minimal
hurricane strength briefly before hitting Mexican coast last month.
</TEXT>
