<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PostEditor     09-11 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Post Editor,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>C. David Burgin Named Editor-in-Chief of The Houston Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former editor of the Dallas Times Herald, C.
David Burgin, has been named vice president and editor-in-chief of
The Houston Post, the newspaper announced.
   Burgin, 49, succeeds Peter O'Sullivan, 39, who said he was
resigning to pursue other opportunities, the Post reported
Saturday. Burgin was editor of the Times Herald until June and is a
longtime associate of William Dean Singleton, whose Houston-based
MediaNews Group owns the Post.
   Singleton said he has known Burgin since 1977. ``His newspapers
have warmth. They have personality,'' Singleton said.
   Singleton also praised O'Sullivan for his accomplishments since
taking over as editor in December 1983. ``The Post under Peter made
dramatic improvements,'' he said.
   Earlier last week, the Post announced that Publisher Don Hunt
was moving to head a new international division of MediaNews. Hunt
had stayed on at the newspaper after the Toronto Sun Publishing Co.
sold it to Singleton's company a year ago. Singleton replaced Hunt
as publisher.
   Burgin said Ernie Williamson will remain as the paper's managing
editor.
   Burgin also was editor of the Washington Star, the Peninsula
Times Tribune in Palo Alto, Calif., the Orlando Sentinel and the
San Francisco Examiner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
