<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DelawarePrimary 6thLd-Writethru a0401 09-11 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Primary, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0401,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lt. Gov. Woo Loses Primary Battle for Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with quotes from
Beard and Woo. Picks up 4th graf pvs `Beard faces...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wealthy civic activist won an upset victory
over Delaware's lieutenent governor Saturday in a Democratic
primary election for the right to challenge a Republican incumbent
in the U.S. Senate.
   With 97 percent or 330 of the 339 precincts reporting, Samuel S.
Beard had 22,418 votes, or 53 percent, to Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo's
19,624 votes, or 47 percent.
   Nine small precincts were not expected to report their results
until Monday, but Woo conceded Saturday night.
   He apologized to his supporters for not running a winning
campaign, and said in a statement, ``I always said it was a tough
way to earn a living,'' according to his press secretary Charles
Siegel.
   ``It was a wonderful victory,'' Beard said, referring to himself
as the underdog in the primary campaign. ``We ran a grassroots
campaign from the beginning. We went into living rooms, all over
the state. We walked through 19 pairs of shoes.''
   Beard faces Sen. William V. Roth Jr. in the November general
election. Roth, who did not have a primary opponent, is seeking a
fourth term.
   The votes represented a little more than a 30 percent turnout of
Democrats eligible to vote in the only statewide race in the
primary, according to John G. Davis Jr., state election
commissioner.
   There were 133,386 Democrats eligible to vote, and average
turnout for a primary is about 20 percent.
   Two Beard campaign workers were detained Saturday night after an
officer caught them taking down about 50 Woo signs throughout New
Castle before dawn Saturday, police said.
   Authorities planned to charge the men with theft and conspiracy,
but a Woo assistant asked that no charges be filed, police said.
   There was no indication Beard had ordered the signs destroyed.
   ``They took them back to the New Castle Armory Building where
Sam Beard's headquarters are located, and they were putting them
into a dumpster there when a town resident called to report the
incident,'' New Castle Police Sgt. Patrick B. Cannon said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Woo, 51, born in Shanghai, China, had the financial support of
Asian-American communities, for whom he has become a champion
nationwide.
   Woo, a physics professor at the University of Delaware, was a
political newcomer four years ago when he beat two legislators in a
primary, then went on to win the lieutenant governor's seat by a
slim 479 votes.
   Beard, 49, who inherited his wealth, had the support of party
leaders and loyalists, as well as unions. He is a former staffer of
the late Robert Kennedy, and runs a nonprofit company that helps
attract grants and designs plans to attract economic development.
   Beard was far outspent by Woo.
   Campaign finance reports filed in late August showed Woo with
$407,998 on hand. Beard had only $65,008. Roth had $734,933.
   Woo's ethnic background was targeted recently in an open letter
supporting Beard that was written by Edward ``Pete'' Peterson,
president of the state AFL-CIO.
   The letter said in part: ``It is up to you and I to save this
country not only from the Asian influences the lieutenant governor
refers to, but all foreign influence.''
   Last week, Peterson wrote another letter, apologizing to anyone
who might have been offended by the statement. Peterson said he was
referring to Woo's claims that he has many contact with business
leaders in Asia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
