<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MissAmerica 6thLd-Writethru a0418 09-11 1039</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss America, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0418,1067</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss Minnesota Becomes Miss America 1989</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CLARIFIES in 2nd graf year she will reign; clarifies tie in
11th graf `But getting...' and in 27th graf ``She also...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotoXACC1, XACC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Minnesota Gretchen Elizabeth
Carlson, who wants to be a Harvard-trained lawyer, became the first
classical violinist to win the Miss America crown in a contest that
required two polls of the judges Saturday night.
   Miss Carlson erupted in tears as her name was announced as Miss
America 1989. She laughed and cried as she took her victory walk
along the runway at Convention Center.
   The first runner-up was Miss Colorado Maya Walker, 23, of Vail;
the second runner-up was Miss Oklahoma Lori Lee Kelley, 23, of
Clinton; the third runner-up was Miss California Marlise Sharleen
Ricardos, 26, of San Pedro; and the fourth runner-up was Miss
Alabama Jenny Lee Jackson, 21, of Auburn.
   Miss Carlson, 22, of Anoka, is a senior at the prestigious
Stanford University in California, majoring in organizational
behavior. As part of her studies, she spent a semester at Oxford
University in England. She plans to attend Harvard Law School.
   ``I'm not a beauty queen. I aspire to go to Harvard Law School.
This is not just for someone who is beautiful. This is for someone
who is educated and sophisticated,'' Miss Carlson told reporters
after winning.
   She said she felt ``shocked inside. I'm trying to remain
composed on the outside.''
   Asked about the first thing she wanted to do, she replied, ``Eat
pizza. That's all I can think about.''
   The 5-foot-3, 108-pound Miss Carlson impressed judges with a
spirited violin piece titled ``Gypsy Airs.'' The piece started slow
and moving, then jumped into a splashy, fast-paced beat.
   Miss Carlson's father, Lee, who attended the pageant, said his
daughter is ``a winner. Everything she does she gives 110 percent.
She doesn't like to lose.''
   Her mother, Karen Carlson, added: ``I think it feels wonderful.
She said she knew she could win.''
   But getting Miss Carlson's name from the judges was not easy. As
television host Gary Collins walked to the judge's area in front of
the stage to learn who had won, he was told there was a tie. It
later turned out to be a tie for second and third places.
   In an affort to kill time, Collins nervously began making small
talk with the contestants.
   There was a flurry of activity in the judge's box.
   Pageant Director Leonard Horn, sitting next to the judges,
tapped his fingers on the edge of the stage as a discussion took
place on what to do.
   Eventually, a second poll of the judges resulted in Miss Carlson
taking the coveted rhinestone-studded headpiece.
   During the wait, Miss Carlson said things were tense on stage.
   ``At that moment, I thought, `Oh, it's all over,''' she said.
   After winning a preliminary talent competition earlier in the
week, Miss Carlson termed parts of her performance ``exquisite''
but vowed to do even better on the final night. She has studied the
violin for 17 years.
   For her performance, the green-eyed blonde wore a black velvet
gown with a sweetheart neckline with dramatic green lame-puffed
sleeves and pleated layered skirts.
   Miss Carlson, who prides herself on being 100 percent Swedish,
had taken special pains during the week to highlight her heritage.
At the Miss America parade on Tuesday, her hair and dress were
decorated with a traditional garland of flowers.
   However, for the evening gown competition, Miss Carlson chose a
long-sleeved turquoise, beaded gown with a silver-beaded design on
the bodice and back.
   Horn, in his first year as the pageant's executive director, has
stressed that the new Miss America will fit into a different mold
than tradition previously held.
   ``Multi-faceted young women who are more than just physically
attractive and talented'' have become the ideal, he said. ``These
are dynamic young college women.''
   In an effort to prove that to a national television audience
Saturday night, the pageant televised video clips of the finalists'
interviews that was part of preliminary judging. Also, the judges
on Saturday night asked an unrehearsed question of each of the top
10 finalists during the evening gown competition.
   The new Miss America succeeds Miss America 1988 Kaye Lani Rae
Rafko, 25, an outspoken nurse from Monroe, Mich., who has
championed AIDS education and safe sex, and preferred to make
charity appearances rather than take paid engagements during the
year.
   Collins returned for his seventh year as host of the finals to
croon the pageant standard ``There She Is'' to the new queen.
Collins' wife, Miss America 1959 Mary Ann Mobley, co-hosted this
year's pageant with the theme ``Success.''
   She also joined Collins in attempting to kill network air time
as the judge's tried to come up with a winner. Pageant officials
said there have been a number of tie situations in years past.
   The 67-year-old Miss America Pageant is the largest contributor
of scholarships to young women, awarding more than $5 million in
scholarships annually to more than 80,000 young women who compete
on the national, state and local levels.
   The new Miss America receives a $30,000 cash scholarship and the
income from a year of personal appearances. Miss Rafko estimates
she earned more than $150,000 during her reign.
   The first runner-up receives a $17,000 scholarship and the next
three runners-up receive $11,000, $8,000 and $6,000 in
scholarships, respectively.
   The remaining finalists each receive $4,000 to be used toward
their educations, and every remaining contestant receives a $2,000
scholarship.
   This year, a new judging system was introduced. The contestants
were interviewed and judged in preliminary competitions by a
preliminary panel of seven judges. On Saturday, a panel of 12
celebrity judges started from scratch after reviewing videos of the
top 10 finalists' interviews.
   Saturday's celebrity judges were: actors Richard Dysart and
Blair Underwood of television's ``L.A. Law''; NBC News
correspondent Deborah Norville; Miss America 1971 and broadcaster
Phyllis George; actor George Peppard; actress Eva Gabor; columnist
Dr. Joyce Brothers; Olympic ice skating gold medalist Brian
Boitano; movie producer Lili Fini Zanuck; model agency founder
Eileen Ford; Parade magazine publisher Walter Anderson; and William
Farley, chairman of Farley Industries.
</TEXT>
