<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Delta-Investigation 1stLd-Writethru a0639 09-11 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta-Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0639,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Physician Says Captain Not Well Enough To Be Interviewed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS lead to flight 1141, sted 1411</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of Delta Flight 1141 is not well
enough to talk to federal investigators about the Aug. 31 crash
that killed 13 people, his physician said Saturday.
   Dr. William Thompson issued a statement saying he alone is
responsible for denying investigators from the National
Transportation Safety Board or anyone else a chance to interview
Capt. Larry Davis about the crash.
   NTSB officials have complained that they were being kept away
from the Delta captain by overprotective Air Line Pilots
Association and Delta Air Lines officials.
   Davis is at Parkland Memorial Hospital, where he is being
treated for back and facial injuries, a hospital spokesman said. He
is listed in good condition.
   Thompson ``hasn't given any permission to anyone to talk to
Capt. Davis,'' said the hospital's administrative resident, Paula
Turner.
   Thompson, the assistant director of surgery for the University
of Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas, said Davis will
cooperate with the NTSB investigation later, when his medical
condition improves.
   ``Tentatively, Capt. Davis may talk with the NTSB early next
week, depending on his condition, which may change from day to
day,'' Thompson said in his statement.
   Davis, who was fitted with a back brace Thursday, was up and
walking in his hospital room Friday, Delta spokesman Neil Monroe
said. He also is recuperating from surgery on Tuesday for a
fractured cheekbone.
   Davis was at the controls of the 15-year-old Boeing 727 when it
crashed at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport seconds after
takeoff. Thirteen died and 95 others, including the three-man
cockpit crew, survived.
   Co-pilot Carey Wilson Kirkland Jr., 37, who was released from
Northeast Community Hospital in Bedford on Friday, told
investigators he could not remember anything from the time the
plane left the terminal.
   Flight engineer Steven M. Judd, 31, told investigators that the
aircraft's right wing dropped severely shortly after takeoff and
that the airplane veered to the right. Judd said that he heard no
abnormal engine sounds, but that someone in the cockpit had called
out an engine failure.
   NTSB officials have said their inquiry is focusing on possible
problems with the jet's wing flaps and its three Pratt & Whitney
JT8D engines.
   Friends of Davis who have visited the pilot in the hospital said
that Davis told them that the plane's wing flaps were properly set
for takeoff but that the aircraft did not have enough power.
</TEXT>
