<1ST_LINE>u a BC-MarketShootings     09-11 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Market Shootings,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Killing Five at Supermarket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 27-year-old man was convicted Saturday night
for slaying five people and wounding two others during a
supermarket robbery.
   Marvin Jennings showed no emotion as the verdict was read, but
his mother and sister were in tears, as were the relatives of some
victims.
   He was convicted of five counts of first-degree murder, two
counts of first-degree assault, one count of first-degree robbery
and eight counts of armed criminal action.
   Prosecutor Gary Randall said he will seek the death penalty in
sentencing hearings set for Tuesday.
   Defense attorney Brad Kessler said he would appeal the verdict.
   ``I can't second-guess what happened in the jury room,'' Kessler
said, noting that the jury was earlier reported to be widely split
on a decision. ``They were under tremendous pressure. You never
know what a jury's going to do.''
   After closing arguments Friday night, the jury met for several
hours, then resumed deliberations Saturday morning. The verdict
came more than 15 hours later.
   Another suspect, Donnie Blankenship, 26, is scheduled to go on
trial later.
   Kessler maintained his client had nothing to do with the crime.
He brought several witnesses to the trial in an effort to prove
that police had used coercion on some of the initial suspects in
the case.
   Investigators said Jennings and Blankenship entered the National
supermarket in north St. Louis after it had closed Sept. 4, 1987,
possibly by posing as a cleaning crew. A security guard was taken
by surprise and was killed, and six other employees were ordered to
lie on the floor and were shot in the back of the head. Two of the
shooting victims survived.
</TEXT>
