<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 2ndLd-Writethru   09-11 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0572,0864</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Multiparty Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Parliament approval,
election supervisors appointed, other details; pickup 6th graf pvs,
`Power corrupts ...' Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Maung Maung on Saturday bowed to
massive pro-democracy protests and announced that the ruling party
would relinquish its 26-year monopoly on power and hold multiparty
elections.
   An emergency session of Parliament on Sunday approved multiparty
elections in about three months and appointed a group of elders to
supervise polling.
   But key opposition leaders pressed for more political
concessions, including an interim government to cope with Burma's
growing chaos, and sporadic protests continued.
   Millions of people have taken to the streets since March to call
for democracy in Burma.
   The Parliament authorized the Council of State, Burma's highest
governent body, to hold elections in as early as 45 days or the
postpone them beyond the tentative three-month date if necessary.
   It also empowered the council to make necessary changes in the
constitution to reflect a multiparty system, enlarge an Elections
Supervision Commission if necessary and formulate election rules.
   Named to the Elections Supervision Commission were three retired
civil servants, a retired army brigadier and a former member of
Parliament. All are more than 70 years old.
   On Saturday, speaking before 968 delegates at a special party
congress, Maung Maung acknowledged that the party made major errors
and said the interests of the people were paramount.
   
   ``Power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely,'' he
said in a speech carried by the state-owned Radio Rangoon. ``As
members of the ruling party for a long period, they tended to
forget the interests of the people and lose public confidence.''
   The Western-trained lawyer pledged fair and free elections as
soon as possible. He said he would not be a candidate.
   The broadcast announcer said the decision was unanimously
adopted by the delegates of the Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Maung Maung urged government employees, who have gone on strike
in sympathy with the massive pro-democracy movement, to return to
their jobs and revive his stalled government.
   The government move was another retreat in face of the sometimes
bloody nationwide uprising. The movement has prompted the
resignation of two hard-line presidents, the lifting of martial law
and virtually unimpeded political activities that earlier would
have drawn long prison terms or worse.
   Western observers noted that the anti-government surge came
without any outside support or meaningful resort to arms, although
demonstrators often have compared their movement with those of
other Asian countries.
   ``They were inspired by the triumph of People's Power in the
Philippines ... They were encouraged by the establishment of
democracy in South Korea last year,'' U.S. Rep. Steven Solarz,
D-N.Y., said after returning from Rangoon earlier last week.
   In Washington, the State Department took a cautious stance.
   ``It's still not clear the date or the manner of the elections
that would be held, or whether the government's move will satisfy
the desires of the people,'' spokesman Dennis G. Harter said.
   Maung Maung's government originally planned to meet Monday to
consider a referendum on a general election and a multiparty system.
   On Friday, opposition leader former prime minister U Nu, who was
toppled from power in a 1962 military coup by Ne Win, defied
Burma's authoritarian rulers and declared the formation of a rival
government and elections Oct. 9.
   But three top members of the rival goverment resigned Saturday,
and reliable sources said U Nu had not consulted them about the
announcement.
   Although U Nu, 82, is respected by a large number of Burmese,
diplomats say his age makes it unlikely that he will be anything
more than a ``symbol'' of continuing opposition to authoritarian
diehards.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, an opposition figure and daughter of the
deceased national hero Aung San, told reporters that Saturday's
announcement was ``a positive step,'' but said it could take up to
two years to form parties to contest in general elections.
   ``Under the present economic and political situation, an interim
government will be the best solution. It (interim government) would
deal with economic problems and also hold general elections,'' she
told newsmen.
   Many opposition figures demanded that an interim government be
set up immediately.
   ``Every minute the economic, political and security situation
deteriorates,'' one opposition lawyer said. ``Immediate formation
of an interim government is the only solution. The country won't
hold up until these general elections.''
   Ne Win resigned as head of the ruling party in July, citing in
part widespread street protests in March and June.
   Riots flared when the party chose as his successor Sein Lwin,
who is widely hated for his brutal suppression of dissidents.
Troops fired into crowds of protesters, and the government said 112
people were killed. Western diplomats said the number was much
higher.
   Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12 after 17 days in power, and Maung
Maung was named to replace him. Maung Maung was Burma's first
civilian leader in 26 years.
</TEXT>
