<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DuneShacks     09-11 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dune Shacks,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Push For Preservation Of Cape Cod's Rustic Dune Shacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of Congress are urging the
National Park Service to abandon its plan to tear down the rustic
shacks on remote dunes of Cape Cod, Mass., that have inspired
artists and authors including playwright Eugene O'Neill.
   The park service argues that the 18 dune shacks do not have
architectural significance and therefore should not be placed on
the National Register of Historic Places.
   Three Massachusetts Democrats, Sens. Edward M. Kennedy and John
F. Kerry and Rep. Gerry E. Studds, who represents the Cape, are
joining state and local officials in a fight to save the primitive
huts from destruction.
   ``These buildings represent a unique aspect of American history
and culture that should be preserved for future generations,'' they
wrote William Penn Mott, director of the National Park Service,
last week. ``We believe the dune shacks are indeed historic
structures.''
   The shacks, nestled in a two-mile strip of dunes in Truro and
Provincetown at the far end of the Cape, were originally built by
the Coast Guard as shelters from harsh coastal weather. They became
part of the park service's domain in 1961 when President Kennedy
created the Cape Cod National Seashore.
   The shacks' preservation has become an emotional issue in recent
years because the expiration of one-time leases signed when the
national seashore was created, usually for the owner's lifetime or
25 years.
   Preservationists want the federal government to declare the
shacks historic treasures and allow a private organization to
mantain them for public use.
   A study commissioned by the park service concluded that the
primitive structures do not qualify for National Register
protection. But critics say the study focused on the buildings'
lack of architectural importance and ignored their historical and
cultural significance that some proponents compare to that of
Walden Pond, home of Henry David Thoreau.
   With local support growing in favor of preserving the shacks,
the Massachusetts Historical Commission is expected to vote
Wednesday in Boston to urge federal officials to save the
buildings. The park service said it will issue a statement at that
meeting.
   ``I am hopeful that they will decide that in years to come, many
more people will have the same oppportunity for inspiration that
the dune shacks have offered Eugene O'Neill, Harry Kemp, Norman
Mailer and many others,'' Studds said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
