<DOCNO> AP880911-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarvardStudy     09-11 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Study,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Freshman Want More Study Time, Less Class Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The typical Harvard freshman spends
nearly 41 hours a week in class or studying, doesn't go to sleep
until after 1 a.m., and sometimes loses effectiveness because of
weariness, depression and stress, according to a recent study.
   Keith W. Light, a doctoral candidate in education at Harvard,
asked 63 first-year students to log their days 15 minutes at a time
for one week in March and one week in April.
   ``We assume that because they're coming to Harvard they have
their acts together in every way,'' he said. ``I don't think that's
true, having been a proctor (adviser) living in a freshman dorm for
three years.''
   The study was intended to determine if a time-logging exercise
might be useful to new students and their advisers in helping the
students make better use of their time.
   ``I've always been interested in the freshman experience of
getting used to college life,'' Light said. ``It seems to be that
the actual use of time not only affects a first-year student
academically but also their sense of fulfillment and enjoyment in
the experience.''
   Fifty-six percent of the students said on at least one day that
they were too weary to be productive. Thirty-seven percent said
depression, frustration or stress made them unproductive.
   In addition to logging each period's activities, students were
asked to indicate which ones were most valuable and which were a
waste of time. Television was listed as a common time-waster, but
more students mentioned at least once that a class or a lab was a
waste of time.
   Forty-four percent said they wasted time watching television on
at least one day during the survey period, but 62 percent thought
classes were a waste of time and 54 percent felt labs were little
help. Just 6 percent reported that they wasted time on drinking or
a hangover at least once during the survey period.
   The students said they devoted an average of 5.83 hours a day,
or 40.8 hours a week, to academics, including class time, study
time and lab time. Students generally spend about 15 hours a week
in the classroom, Light said.
   Light said he did not seek a random sample for his survey, but
he got a good cross-section of the freshman class by simply asking
students in two sections of one dormitory to participate.
   He said the 63 respondents from the 1,600-member class was about
twice the minimum sample group for a survey.
   ``It's a carefully done study, but it's modest,'' Light said.
``We're not trying to draw too many earth-shattering
generalizations but get to something that will help them put their
time togther.''
   Seventy-three percent said in retrospect they would have changed
the way they spent a day.
   ``While many students could tell you, `Yes, I do procrastinate'
and `Yes, I don't get enough sleep sometimes' and `I know if I
studied without heavy metal (rock music) in the background I might
be able to concentrate,' the exercise seems to be able to give
students a more realistic views of how they spend their time,''
Light said.
   During school nights, the students got an average of 7.5 hours
of sleep on a school night, but not by going to bed early.
   Seventy-five percent of the students said they didn't get to bed
until after midnight and 61 percent said they were usually up past
1 a.m. Even at 3 a.m., some 12 percent were awake.
   Light conducted follow-up interviews with 24 students and said
most of them found the exercise useful in evaluating the way they
spend their time. This fall, officials asked Light to make the
exercise available to all freshmen who might find it helpful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
