<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Charles-HongKong     09-11 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Charles-Hong Kong,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Suggests Prince Could Be Hong Kong Governor: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has suggested to
Prince Charles that he become governor of Hong Kong in time to hand
the British colony over to China in 1997, a newspaper reported
Sunday.
   The Sunday Times of London quoted from a new biography of the
heir to the British throne, ``Charles,'' by journalist Anthony
Holden. The paper owns the newspaper rights to the book.
   Holden's book says the Hong Kong suggestion was made during a
March 25 meeting between Charles and Mrs. Thatcher at the prince's
London residence, Kensington Palace.
   It followed ``a discussion of the prince's wish that he might in
the longer term be accorded some sort of title to reflect his
increased status in national affairs,'' Holden says in his book.
   However, the appointment of Britain's governor to Hong Kong, one
of the most sensitive posts in Britain's diplomatic service, is
made by Charles' mother, Queen Elizabeth II, not the prime minister.
   Buckingham Palace had no comment on the report, and a spokesman
for Mrs. Thatcher's 10 Downing St. office said Sunday, ``We never
comment on any contacts between the prime minister and members of
the royal family.''
   Holden attributes his information to two separate sources he
says are confidants of the prince's, the newspaper said.
   The author said in a television interview Sunday that Charles,
who celebrates his 40th birthday in November, ``still feels despite
everything that people think he hasn't got a proper job.''
   Charles has been training all his life to succeed his mother,
who is 62 years old and in good health.
   Holden said he thinks the prince would welcome the Hong Kong job
``because it would be seen to give him a higher profile in national
life ... he would be seen to be doing something on the forefront of
the international stage.''
</TEXT>
