<2ND_LINE>AM-Bag Baby,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Finds Infant In Grocery Bag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 88-year-old woman trying to do her
part to clean up litter was shocked when the discarded grocery bag
she was picking up began moving. Inside was a newborn girl.
   ``I thought, `Well, I'd better pick that garbage up,'''
Katherine Sword said after the child was found Saturday.
   ``Then something moved,'' she said. ``I thought it was a snake
at first, but then I saw the little fingers coming up. I said, `Oh
my Lord, it's a baby, a baby.'
   ``I was awfully shocked to find out it was a baby,'' Ms. Sword
said. ``She didn't cry a bit. Usually, a newborn baby hollers like
the dickens.''
   The 6-pound, 2-ounce infant girl was listed in stable condition
Sunday at St. Mary's Hospital in West Palm Beach.
   Police believe she was born about 30 minutes before Ms. Sword
found her. They were attempting to identify the child's mother, who
could face child abuse charges.
   Hospital spokesman Don Chester said the infant, named only
``Girl Doe'' for the time being, ``appears to be a healthy baby.
When a baby is born outside a hospital, and you don't know the
history ... you always take a wait-and-see attitude.''
   Ms. Sword was returning from the library about 1 p.m. Saturday
when she found the baby. Without touching the infant, she ran to
her apartment and called police.
   ``I was a little worried because it didn't move, but then it
cried,'' said paramedic Ron Rudy.
   Cam Freedlund, a spokeswoman for the state health department,
said the child probably would be placed in a foster home, unless
social workers find that the parents or grandparents are capable of
caring for a newborn.
   ``If I wasn't such a stickler for picking garbage from the
sidewalk, it might not have been found,'' Ms. Sword said.
   ``That was a rough way to leave a child like that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
