<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Improved Chinese-Soviet Ties Won't Harm Chinese-US
Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improved ties between the Soviet Union and
China will help world peace and will not hurt the close bonds
between China and the United States, U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci said Sunday.
   ``Our position is that we welcome this dialogue (between the
Soviet Union and China). ... It would be healthy for world peace
and stability,'' Carlucci told the Young Presidents' Organization,
meeting in this British colony.
   Carlucci said America's relationship with China is ``solid''
even if China develops closer relations with the Soviet Union.
   In recent years, China and the Soviet Union have tried to
improve their relations after an era of estrangement over political
and ideological differences.
   Carlucci arrived in Hong Kong on Saturday from China, where he
met Deng Xiaoping and other leaders. He left for Washington after
addressing the Young Presidents' Organization, a private education
and service group based in New York whose 6,000 members became
presidents of their companies before they were 40.
   Carlucci said that in his Beijing talks, it was ``fascinating to
see the confluence of interests'' between China and the United
States on Afghanistan, Cambodia and other international issues.
   On Friday in Washington, the U.S. government announced it would
approve export licenses for satellites manufactured by the U.S.
Hughes Aircraft Co. to be launched by China with its Long March
rocket.
   Private U.S. companies trying to establish satellite launching
services have said they could be priced out of the international
market by China's government-supported launching service.
   Carlucci said the Chinese launch prices are about half the cost
of those in the United States, but he did not specify amounts.
   He said he and Chinese Premier Li Peng had discussed the impact
of the Chinese launches on the U.S. defense industry and the
possibility of China adjusting the price and number of its launches.
</TEXT>
