<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     09-11 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Guerrillas Blamed in Villagers' Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil extremists hacked to death 12
people, including five children, and the government implemented a
plan to try to end ethnic violence in two provinces, officials said
Sunday.
   Five others were seriously injured in the attack Saturday in the
eastern village of Suhadagama, said a military spokesman who spoke
on condition of anonymity. Suhadagama is about 150 miles south of
Colombo, the capital.
   The spokesman quoted witnesses as saying about 20 Tamil
militants stabbed the victims with pickaxes, swords and daggers.
   The dead included four Tamils who were married to Sinhalese
women, the spokesman said. Their wives were not hurt, he said.
   The insurgents were blamed for a similar attack two weeks ago in
which 11 Sinhalese farmers were butchered in neighboring
Polonnaruwaq district.
   Tamil rebels want to set up a separate nation in Sri Lanka's
north and east provinces. The insurgents claim both provinces as
their traditional homeland and have been attacking villages to try
to chase away Sinhalese and Moslem settlers.
   Tamils are mostly Hindu and make up 18 percent of the island's
16 million people. They claim they are discriminated against by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise about 75 percent of
the country's population.
   In July 1987, India and Sri Lanka signed a peace accord aimed at
ending five years of bloodshed. India sent an estimated 50,000
troops to Sri Lanka to try to enforce the agreement.
   India became involved in the conflict because it is the regional
power and because more than 60 million Tamils living in southern
India are sympathetic to the rebels' cause.
   A key provision of the agreement calls for the merger of the
north and east provinces. The union then will be governed by an
elected provincial council that would take over most administrative
and political duties now handled by the federal government.
   The government of President Junius R. Jayewardene announced the
merger on Saturday and said it believes a provincial council will
be chosen by January. The rebels have had no response.
   The Tamil separatist campaign, launched in 1983, has claimed at
least 8,500 lives, including more than 550 Indian soldiers. India
says its troops have killed at least 1,000 Tamil insurgents.
</TEXT>
