<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-11 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Protest `Half Olympics'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Olympic City, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students burned an effigy of
President Roh Tae-woo on Sunday and accused the government of
staging the Olympics to strengthen military rule.
   The demonstrations at Seoul's Yonsei University were peaceful
and there were no reports of arrests or injuries, in contrast to
the violent clashes with police on Friday and Saturday.
   ``Oppose the half Olympics!'' shouted about 350 students,
referring to North Korea's boycott of the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 Games in
Seoul after its demand to be a co-host for the Games was denied.
   The protesters chanted ``Yankee go home!'' as they marched to
the front gate of the university in eastern Seoul. The students
charge that the United States is helping the Roh government to use
the Olympics to strengthen what they say is a dictatorial rule.
   ``We do not oppose the Olympics itself,'' said a student, who
requested anonymity. ``But Olympics is staged by a military
government for propaganda purposes. The military government led by
Roh oppresses the masses.''
   Leaflets distributed by students at a rally before the effigy
burning included a picture of the interlocking Olympic rings made
of barbed wire superimposed on a photograph of Olympic Park.
   Several thousand police armed with tear gas and other
riot-control weapons watched the demonstrations from across the
busy street in front of the university. The government has ordered
police to avoid using tear gas during the Olympics.
   Radical students, who have called for anti-Olympic protests,
have so far demonstrated on a few campuses in Seoul and other
cities. They have not protested near the Olympic sites.
   The radicals, a small but vocal minority on campuses, have
virtually no public support among most South Koreans. Many
government officials say they believe radicals are controlled by
communist North Korea.
   Radical students claim that Roh is a front for continued
military rule and say they are determined to topple the government.
   Roh, a former general who won the presidential elections in
December, has introduced broad democratic reforms and dismantled
authoritarian controls. His popularity among the South Korean
people has risen steadily since he took office in February.
   Students marching to Yonsei's main gate on Sunday carried a
6-foot-high pole wrapped in gasoline-soaked rags, with a frowning
paper face representing Roh tied to it. The effigy was torched
while students sang protest songs and marched with flags and
banners. After the demonstration, the students dispersed
voluntarily.
   Protests at Yonsei University erupted into violence Friday and
Saturday when students, some armed with wood and iron clubs, threw
firebombs and rocks at police.
</TEXT>
