<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Vincennes-Compensation     09-11 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes-Compensation,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight 655 Compensation Unlikely Until After Reagan Leaves Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families of the 290 people killed in the U.S.
downing of Iran Air Flight 655 are unlikely to receive compensation
during the remaining months of the Reagan administration, officials
say.
   President Reagan pledged to offer compensation soon after the
U.S.S. Vincennes shot down the plane over the Persian Gulf, but the
plan still faces two steep hurdles _ the bureaucratic and legal
obstacles caused by a lack of communications between the United
States and Iran, and its continued unpopularity on Capitol Hill.
   ``I think we're a long way from payments actually being made, if
they ever actually are,'' said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of
the House Armed Services Committee.
   ``It's a hard sell up here on Capitol Hill. There's not a lot of
support up here for Iran,'' he said. ``And in addition, you have a
lot of questions _ who do you actually pay, how do you get them the
money, how do you make sure it goes to the families and not to the
government of Iran?''
   The case involves the destruction of Iran Air Flight 655, shot
down July 3 by the Navy cruiser Vincennes in the Strait of Hormuz
shortly after taking off from Bandar Abbas. All 290 persons aboard
were killed when the Vincennes fired two missiles in the mistaken
belief that the unidentified plane was an Iranian military F-14.
   U.S. officials expressed regret and Reagan decided July 11 to
offer compensation to families of the victims, but the plan quickly
ran into opposition in Congress. Legislators were reflecting a
decade of public unhappiness with Iran and its leader, Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, dating back to Iran's taking of American
hostages.
   A Navy investigation, headed by Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty,
found last month the shoot-down was due to a series of
stress-caused human mistakes made by a crew in combat for the first
time.
   But the Fogarty report also laid some blame on Iran, criticizing
that country for permitting a commercial airliner to fly over a
Navy warship that had been engaged in a firefight with Iranian
gunboats.
   While the Navy was investigating, the State Department began
trying to answer the myriad of questions raised by Reagan's
announcement.
   For example, the questions of who gets the money is unanswered.
The United States and Iran have no diplomatic relations and Iran
has not yet even furnished a manifest with the names of the
passengers.
   Another question is how much to pay.
   One congressional official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the amounts range from $50,000 to $250,000 per victim.
   Congress will carefully scrutinize any plan the State Department
develops.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said, ``I'm willing to consider
compensation, but I don't want one penny to go to the government of
Iran.''
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., said the Fogarty report underscores the
need for compensation, ``but we have to be careful that none of the
money goes to the government.''
   While the United States is offering compensation, U.S. officials
point out that the Soviet Union has refused to pay anything for two
incidents in which the Soviets shot down Korean Airline planes. In
one incident, in 1978, two passengers were killed, and in the
other, in 1983, 269 people were killed, including 60 Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880911-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Trouble-shooter     09-11 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Trouble-shooter,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Leadership Style: Cautious Trouble-shooter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wity AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scrawled note by Michael Dukakis about a
controversial prison project turned out to be prophetic: ``This
spells mucho trouble. Let's discuss. MSD.''
   Later, the Massachusetts governor penned another message to his
legal counsel on a plan to build a prison in the tiny central town
of New Braintree: ``No further action until we discuss. MSD.''
   The Democratic presidential nominee had correctly predicted the
storm of controversy that would surround the plan. But his 1985
notes displayed something else about Dukakis that has become more
visible on the campaign trail: his instinctive caution when he
smells trouble.
   That has been the Dukakis management style through recent,
largely crisis-free years, as governor. The style, born of a
first-term disaster, has been an easy one to adopt in a state with
a boom economy and little opposition from Republicans.
   But on the campaign trail, as the presidential race tightens and
he comes under relentless criticism by Vice President George Bush,
Dukakis has given indications that he wants to turn more aggressive.
   That was much in evidence when he re-hired John Sasso, the
campaign chief who was ousted after releasing the tape that led to
Delaware Sen. Joseph Biden's withdrawal from the presidential race.
   Dukakis took some heat for the decision. But he got his way, and
fallout was minimized by his timing: he made the announcement at
the start of the long Labor Day weekend.
   ``I don't think he sees himself as a great risk-taker. He
doesn't place a high value on that,'' said Martin Linsky, a
lecturer at the John F. Kennedy School of Government who was a
Republican colleague in the state Legislature.
   Dukakis' cautious approach to the Sasso affair reflected lessons
he learned in 1975, when, trying to keep a strong campaign promise
of ``no new taxes,'' he held out until forced to impose tax
increases and spending cuts that angered both the right and left.
   ``Going down the street with him, the verbal abuse he would take
from people was quite unbelievable,'' said Thomas P. O'Neill III,
son of the former House speaker and Dukakis' lieutenant governor in
1975. ``I really think he had such confidence in his ability to
handle the (deficit) problem that that would have an overriding
effect on the public relations end of the problem.''
   Joseph Grandmaison, chairman of the New Hampshire Democratic
Party, managed Dukakis' 1974 campaign for governor and recalls a
politician much more willing to make snap decisions then than he is
now. ``Back in the early '70s he was far more likely to look at a
situation and come to an immediate conclusion about what was the
best way to proceed,'' he said.
   The lesson was clear, said Paul Garrity, the former judge who
pushed the administration into the Boston Harbor cleanup project:
``Once burned, twice shy.''
   After he won back the governorship in 1982, Dukakis kept a tight
rein on news emanating from the governor's office and from the many
state agencies. No press release bearing Dukakis' name went out
without being personally checked by the governor. Press aides kept
lists of ``good'' and ``bad'' reporters, broken down by those whose
coverage favored or hurt the administration.
   ``He's taken more seriously the communications aspect of
government,'' Linsky said.
   The much-heralded transformation of Dukakis from his early years
in office to his two recent terms was not entirely complete, Linsky
said. Dukakis once again this year finds himself wrestling with a
state budget shortfall. Although the crisis isn't as serious as in
Dukakis' first term, he has had to sign a cigarette tax into law to
help raise tax revenues.
   ``One of the ways to think about the pattern of not dealing with
revenue problems until fairly late in the game is that if he
doesn't want it to be a problem, he doesn't see it as a problem,''
Linsky said.
   In 1986, Dukakis used the hunker-down approach to distance
himself from disclosures that state officials had approved a
$10,000 payment to silence a student who charged a state college
president with sexual assault.
   The governor recalled first hearing about the alleged assault
and the payoff in January 1986. He said he told a top state
education official to ``get on it'' and ``take care of it.'' But
Dukakis did nothing further to investigate until the story
intensified six months later.
   For more than a year Dukakis let two top administration
officials handle questions on the New Braintree prison issue even
amid charges _ later refuted _ that Dukakis had granted a personal
favor to friends who owned the prison site.
   He also kept a back seat when a prison furlough program that he
deeply believed in came under fire when a convicted murderer on
furlough terrorized a Maryland couple. He reversed the furlough
policy as public opinion was reaching a crescendo.
   But a cautious approach to governing that kept Dukakis out of
trouble in Massachusetts hasn't translated into safety on the
campaign trail.
   Early this month Bush scored political points by coming to
polluted Boston Harbor to highlight an example of what he called
the consequences of excessive delay. Dukakis was forced to defend
himself by saying that after a decade as governor, something was
finally being done to clean the harbor.
</TEXT>
