<DOCNO> AP880911-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iraq-ChemicalWeapons Bjt   09-11 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Chemical Weapons, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Worry Chemical Weapons May Be Returning to Vogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's use of poison gas against its Kurdish
minority is prompting concern that other nations bogged down in
armed conflict might resort to the ``silent killer'' in violation
of a universally accepted ban on use of chemical weapons.
   According to U.S. officials, there is little question that
Iraq's use of mustard gas against Iranian forces influenced Iran's
decision to end their eight-year old Persian Gulf war last month.
   Almost immediately after the cease-fire took effect, Iraq
launched an offensive against its Kurdish minority as suspected
collaborators with Iran. Tens of thousands of Kurds were forced to
flee into southern Turkey.
   Last week, about nine days after the first reports of Iraqi
chemical warfare began to circulate, Secretary of State George P.
Shultz said he was convinced the allegations were true.
   Shultz accused the Iraqis of ``unjustifiable and abhorrent''
behavior. The Senate then unanimously approved stringent economic
sanctions against Iraq.
   Iraq's minister of state for foreign affairs, Saddoun Hammadi,
met with Shultz on Thursday and called the charges ``absolutely
baseless.''
   But well before the latest Iraqi assault on the Kurds, a number
of United Nations investigations concluded that Iraq _ and to a
lesser extent, Iran _ had engaged in chemical warfare since 1984.
   The State Department has sharply criticized Iraq from time to
time and unanimous U.N. Security Council resolutions have done the
same. But the international reaction generally has been muted and
unsustained, possibly reflecting the lack of global sympathy for
Iran's fundamentalist Islamic regime.
   Last May, Iran complained that the absence of punitive measures
against Iraq was having a ``disastrous'' effect. Indeed, a U.N.
report issued two months later said that use of chemical weapons
against Iran was ``intensifying and has become more frequent.''
   The 1925 Geneva convention banning use of chemical weapons,
which was signed by 105 nations, was seen as a major step toward
humanizing armed conflict and assuring that the horrors of poison
and nerve gas attacks in World War I would never be repeated.
   That optimistic view has been changed by the Persian Gulf war
and its ghastly aftermath, foreign affairs analysts say. They are
now concernd that other war-weary nations may conclude that the
benefits of using chemical weapons may outweigh the costs.
   Some U.S. officials privately share the conclusion of Steven
Rose, a neurobiologist at Britain's Open University, who was quoted
in Time magazine as saying that despite a ``major act of genocide,
the fact is, Iraq has got away with it.''
   Elisa Harris, of Britain's Royal United Services Institute,
agrees with that assessment, according to Time. She said other
Third World countries might follow Iraq's example believe that they
``might not have to pay a high political price.''
   The Geneva convention outlaws use of ``asphyxiating, poisonous
or other gases and of bacteriological methods of warfare'' that can
cause vomiting, choking and skin irritation or worst, a speedy
death.
   In 1915, when exposed to German-deployed lethal chlorine near
the Belgian town of Ypres, 5,000 French troops were killed and
10,000 others injured in a single afternoon. World War I claimed an
estimated 91,000 soldiers dead and 1.2 million wounded of gas
attacks by both sides.
   Although 60 million are said to have died during World War II,
chemical weapons were not used, possibly because of the deterrent
effect of knowing that all sides had extensive chemical arsenals.
   President Nixon banned manufacture of chemical weapons in 1969
but President Reagan ordered its resumption last December in the
belief that a new deterrent was needed.
   The United States and the Soviet Union have discussed ways to
limit chemical weapons, and the issue is being debated by a
40-nation Conference on Disarmament.
   But progress toward agreement has been slow, and the State
Department is worried there may be a trend toward greater
proliferation of chemical weaponry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
