<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US Blacks,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Church Group Finally Allowed To Enter Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of black churchgoers from Florida was
allowed to enter Israel on Sunday, two days after being turned away
on suspicion some belonged to a controversial sect, a Foreign
Ministry official said.
   The 35 followers of the Rev. S.D. James of Opa-locka, Fla.,
charged Friday they were harassed by Israeli border guards at
Jordan's Allenby Bridge crossing and denied access to the West
Bank. Opa-locka is 12 miles north of Miami.
   The Israeli official said Sunday the group was stopped because
``there were suspicions that 10 of the group belonged to the Black
Hebrews.''
   Israel has long had a dispute with the predominantly American
Black Hebrews sect, which claims its members are Jewish and have
the right to settle in the Jewish state.
   ``Everything was clarified, and this morning they were allowed
to cross the bridge into Israel,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. He did not elaborate.
   James on Friday accused Israeli soldiers of shoving members of
his group and forcing them back onto their bus. James said he
formally complained to the U.S. Embassy in the Jordanian capital of
Amman.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East war.
