<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YellowstoneReax     09-11 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Reax,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Somber After Viewing Yellowstone Fire Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top government officials touring
Yellowstone National Park expressed shock at the extent of forest
fire damage and promised changes in firefighting policies and more
soldiers to battle the flames.
   ``There's no way you can capture the thing like being here,''
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng said. ``Just look at it _
devastating. ... Look at the natural beauty that's been interfered
with.''
   ``I think it's devastating. We've said before, it's a
disaster,'' Interior Secretary Donald Hodel replied when asked his
impressions during the stopover Saturday at Yellowstone.
   ``The extent of the burned area we've just driven through is
more than you can imagine,'' Hodel added.
   Officials who briefed them were not optimistic about getting the
situation in hand anytime soon.
   ``The potential for controlling these fires is not very great,''
Lyng said. ``This is a terribly difficult situation.''
   Montana Gov. Ted Schwinden, who along with Wyoming Gov. Mike
Sullivan joined the Washington officials on the visit, was somber
after hearing a briefing on the fire situation.
   Schwinden said the officials were told: ```There are three
breaks you can get as firefighters. One is a break in the weather,
a break in the topography, and a break in fuels.'
   ``I asked, if there's no break in the weather, are there breaks
in fuels or topography? And they haven't worked to this point. So
unless we see some major precipitation, I think we'll see a
substantial spread'' of the fires.
   Unless there is generous snow this winter, the area could
actually continue to have fire problems next summer, a veteran
forest ranger said.
   ``We periodically have fires that will hold over through the
winter and start up again in the spring,'' Skip Starkey, a fire
management specialist and 11-year veteran of the Forest Service,
told reporters during Saturday's official tour.
   While the weather may not cooperate, additional human resources
will be sent into action, officials said.
   The Pentagon had earlier supplied about 2,300 Army soldiers from
Fort Lewis, Wash.
   Deputy Defense Secretary William Taft IV announced at Old
Faithful that they would be joined by two Marine battalions _ 1,200
men _ from Camp Pendleton, Calif., and two additional Army
battalions.
   ``So by the end of next week, we will see a doubled
representation by the military in this effort,'' Taft said.
   ``We have a fair amount of air equipment here, and
helicopters,'' Taft added. ``We'll be bringing in more of that,
too.''
   Canadian firefighters also will be pressed into service, thanks
to congressional approval last week of enabling legislation, Lyng
noted.
   Hodel promised at a West Yellowstone news conference that the
Interior Department would make changes in its fire suppression
policies to avoid a similar situation in the future. That brought
applause from an audience of townspeople who have been highly
critical of the way the summer's fires have been handled.
   Hodel and others, however, reiterated their assertion that
nature, not mismanagement, was to blame.
   ``You know, it's OK for people if they want to blame somebody
for what has been a dreadful natural experience,'' Lyng said. ``But
I've been involved all summer with this drought, and I can tell you
that, wherever you go in the North American continent, you see the
effects of the worst drought that we've ever had. And this fire is
one of them.''
   Hodel added: ``This year, if they'd been able to foresee the
kind of conditions we've got, they would have been fighting every
fire from the beginning.
   ``In fact, all the destruction we've driven through was a fire
that they fought from the beginning and couldn't control it,''
Hodel said, referring to the North Fork fire which destroyed
buildings at Old Faithful geyser and threatened West Yellowstone
and park headquarters at Mammoth Hot Springs.
   ``I think the key is to get these fires out, and then review
what's going on,'' Hodel said.
</TEXT>
