<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires-SatelliteTV     09-11 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Satellite TV,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clover-Mist Firefighters Get Satellite TV Dish</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHOSHONE NATIONAL FOREST, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life at the fire camp for
the Clover-Mist forest fire might not be quite as comfortable as
home, but now the firefighters can at least see what's going on in
the rest of the world.
   The camp sits on a sagebrush-covered plateau near the Crandall
Ranger Station along the western border of the Shoshone National
Forest.
   Until Saturday, firefighters with time off from the fire lines
on the 322,000-acre fire relied on a videotape collection of movies
to while away the hours.
   Now they've got a television satellite dish and can tap into
just about anything being broadcast, said Bill Mack, who works for
Rezek Equipment Co., a San Bernardino, Calif., company that
provides fire camp services and which helped arrange for the dish.
   ``This is just so the guys will have something to watch,'' said
Carl Hopkins, who work for Aqua-One, another California company
that normally provides shower and water purification equipment to
fire camps and decided to throw in the satellite dish.
   While it's not unusual for fire camps to have televisions and
videocassette recorders for entertainment, Hopkins said he hasn't
heard of any other camps getting their own satellite dish.
   ``This is kind of an experimental thing,'' agreed Mack.
   The signal from the dish runs to a 40-inch television set in the
``Grand,'' a large canvas tent equipped with 17 log benches and a
wood-burning stove for the cold Wyoming nights.
   Live television isn't the only benefit enjoyed by the
Clover-Mist firefighters. There's a truck-based laundry service
that processes two tons of clothes each day; hot and cold showers;
a small library; and a tent phone booth with two direct-dial phones.
</TEXT>
