<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Non-Aligned     09-11 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministers Criticize U.S. For Supporting Israel, South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of the 101-nation
non-aligned movement Sunday criticized the United States, South
Africa and Israel and expressed support for Nicaragua.
   In a statement at the end of their four-day annual conference,
the ministers charged that the situation in South Africa and Israel
has ``worsened considerably'' and reiterated a call for sanctions
against both.
   The conference, which was attended by 95 of the 101 members,
condemned South Africa for ``acts of genocide'' against its black
population and a ``policy of state terrorism.''
   The ministers ``expressed their indignation and dismay that
certain Western nations ... continued to aid and abet apartheid
economically, financially, politically and diplomatically.''
   They said they regret that efforts by the U.N. Security Council
to impose sanctions on South Africa were blocked by American and
British vetoes.
   The ministers called on the United Nations to take over
``temporary supervision'' of the Israeli-occupied territories to
protect Palestinians from the ``acts of terrorism and atrocities''
by Israel. More than 260 Palestinians have been killed in the
10-month-old uprising, and thousands have been detained. Five
Israelis also have died.
   The non-aligned movement Friday drafted a resolution supporting
the Palestine Liberation Organizaion's plan to declare an
independent Palestinian state in the occupied territories. The
ministers called for the non-aligned movement to financially aid
the Palestinians.
   The resolution emerged from a session by the conference's
nine-member Palestine committee, which includes the PLO, Cuba,
Senegal, India, Yugoslavia, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Algeria and
Bangladesh.
   On another subject in the final statement, the ministers
expressed support for the leftist Sandinista government of
Nicaragua, a member of the non-aligned movement, and demanded an
end to the financing of the U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   In a separate document, the ministers said prospects for the
world economy were ``gloomy'' and that the ``prolonged crisis in
the international economic situation'' was widening the gap between
the developed and the non-aligned and other developing countries.
   The report called for the lowering of interest rates, the
reversal of the flow of resources from developing to developed
countries and an increased access to the markets of the developed
countries.
   The conference also adopted a special ``Nicosia Declaration,''
which mandates a special committee appointed by the conference to
take steps to streamline the organization of the movement.
   Many of the delegates to the conference criticized the
non-aligned movement for becoming stagnated and losing its
credibility.
   The conference ended with the choice by consensus of Yugoslavia
_ one of the founding members of the movement in l961 _ as the host
of next year's summit conference of non-aligned states. This
automatically gives it the chairmanship of the movement for the
next three years.
   Yugoslavia emerged as a compromise when two other declared
candidates, Indonesia and Nicaragua, failed to win a consensus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
