<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires-Ranger     09-11 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Ranger,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Could Continue to Burn Through Winter, Ranger Warns</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unless nature is generous with
moisture in the coming months, fires in Yellowstone National Park
could continue to burn until next summer, a veteran forest ranger
says.
   ``We periodically have fires that will hold over through the
winter and start up again in the spring,'' says Skip Starkey, a
fire management specialist and 11-year veteran of the U.S. Forest
Service.
   ``Certainly there is a possibility for that to happen,'' he
says. ``It would depend on what kind of snow we get this winter,
what kind of rain we get this fall and next spring.''
   Starkey, based at the Bozeman headquarters of the Gallatin
National Forest in Montana, escorted a group of reporters and
photographers Saturday during a visit to the park by Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel, Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng and
Assistant Defense Secretary William Taft IV.
   Although there have been technical advances in fighting forest
fires, including infrared aerial photography, computer modeling and
sophisticated weather analysis, Starkey said:
   ``Firefighting ... is not an exact science by any stretch of the
imagination. There's still a lot of art to it.''
   He pointed out various fire patterns in the lodgepole pine
stands along the 30-mile stretch of road between West Yellowstone
and Old Faithful. In some areas flames skipped randomly, blackening
some trees and sparing others. The fire ``crowned'' other sections
of forest by jumping from treetop to treetop. And in other areas
less-intense flames crept along the ground, leaving an ashen forest
floor but trees that were still green and healthy.
   ``You don't get a continuous, complete burn all over'' in a
forest fire, he explained. ``It's like a mosaic.''
   Starkey said many of the dead trees on the forest floor were
killed not by flames but by lodgepole pine beetles. And with its
shallow root system, the lodgepole pine can easily be blown over in
a stiff wind.
   This provides a major source of fuel for advancing fires, but
the lodgepole pine actually depends on fires to release its seeds
from their cones, Starkey explained.
   During the drive between Old Faithful and West Yellowstone, rain
began to fall.
   ``This sprinkle isn't going to help, except it raises the
humidity,'' Starkey said. ``Spots don't ignite as easily. ...
There's less of a chance it will result in a fire.
   ``This is the biggest benefit from a day like this. You can get
in there and work close to the fire. ... The fire is less able to
generate explosive behavior.''
   But the rain continued and grew from a mere sprinkle to a
respectable drizzle.
   ``That's the kind of weather I like,'' Starkey said. ``I'd like
to see about two weeks of this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
