<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills 10 In Kabul, Another Bomb Hurts 6 In Pakistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with bomb attack in Pakistan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded on a busy street near the
Pakistani Embassy in the Afghan capital Kabul on Sunday, killing 10
people and injuring about 40 others, Tass said.
   The official Soviet news agency blamed Afghan rebels.
   ``The crime prepared and committed by Afghan extremists claimed
the lives of some 10 people, including women and children,'' Tass
said. ``According to preliminary information, another 40 Kabul
residents were injured.''
   A building near the Pakistani Embassy was seriously damaged, as
were 40 stores and 10 cars, Tass said. It provided no other details.
   In Peshawar, Pakistan, near the Afghan border, six people were
injured when a bomb went off in a crowded marketplace near a
garment shop, said a police spokesman.
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosion, but Pakistan
blames such terrorist activities on the Soviet-trained Afghan
secret service Khad. Peshawar in the headquarters of the
anti-communist Afghan guerrilla movement.
   The U.S.-backed insurgents are fighting to overthrow the
Soviet-backed government of President Najib.
   Rocket and other blasts have become almost daily in Kabul, the
Afghan capital, since the Soviet troop withdrawal began on May 15.
   Kabul authorities have blamed all of them on the insurgents, but
Western diplomats believe some bombings are part of long-standing
factional infighting between communists loyal to President Najib
and a rival faction that dominates the military.
   Under an agreement signed April 14, the Soviet government is
withdrawing the estimated 115,000 soldiers it had stationed in
Afghanistan, leaving the fighting to Afghan government forces.
   The Soviet soldiers are to be entirely withdrawn by Feb. 15.
   The Soviet Union and Afghanistan have complained bitterly to the
United Nations and to Pakistani authorities that Pakistan continues
to assist the guerrillas.
   The Soviets entered Afghaninstan in December 1979, replaced one
Marxist regime with another and backed that regime against the
guerrilla uprising.
</TEXT>
