<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor River Phoenix says he is reminded of
his own childhood by his role in the new film, ``Running on
Empty,'' in which he portrays the son of 1960s activists who are
constantly on the move.
   The son of 1960s flower children, Phoenix, 18, says he and his
four brothers grew up poor and moved to Oregon, Florida, South
America and Mexico.
   ``Moving calls for adjusting to a new place and learning not to
get attached,'' he says. ``I liked it because I saw a lot of
different lifestyles.''
   Phoenix and his family now live on a 17-acre farm in Florida.
   The actor says he wants the public to see him as he really is.
He says the images teen magazines paint of him are inaccurate.
Phoenix won't take roles he believes are morally or ethically
wrong. He is a strict vegetarian and more interested in the fate of
the world than money.
   ``I wanted money so we could buy a great place of land and be
self-contained,'' he says. ``That impresses me; that feels good. It
feels like something's been accomplished.''
   Meanwhile, he is considering other movie scripts and will have a
cameo role in the new ``Indiana Jones'' sequel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moved on the sports wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson joined a
Russian Orthodox clergyman and other dignitaries Sunday at the
Soviet Union's first golf course for the opening of the driving
range.
   The golf course, near the Swedish Embassy in south Moscow, is a
project organized by former Swedish hockey player Sven Tumba and
Soviet sports officials.
   Those who attended the opening said they were seeking peace
through sports.
   ``I'm sure that sports promotes friendship and I'm deeply
convinced that the birth of a new game in the Soviet Union will
bring about new contacts among people in various countries who will
find a lot of new friends,'' Tumba said, according to a report by
the Tass news agency.
   Former Brazilian soccer star Pele, who also attended the
opening, said, ``I'm sure that sports will lead to peace in the
world.''
   Tyson is visiting Moscow with his wife, actress Robin Givens,
who is filming episodes of her TV series ``Head of the Class.''
   Plans call for a nine-hole course along the Setun River with
double tees on each hole, allowing it to be used as an 18-hole,
par-68 course.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper capped a week of
celebrations marking his 88th birthday with an outdoor party and
fireworks show at Miami's Bayfront Park.
   ``I'm just pleased that people have been so gracious to me this
week,'' said Pepper, who's been in Congress since 1962 and was a
U.S. senator from 1936-51. About 1,000 people turned out for the
event Saturday evening.
   ``The congressman wanted to share his birthday not just with the
hotshots of Washington, but with the people of South Florida,''
said Miami's vice-mayor, Rosario Kennedy.
   Among those paying tribute to him last week were President
Reagan, Vice President George Bush, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   ``Few legends live long enough to hear themselves called
legends,'' Dukakis said in a message sent to Pepper.
   Pepper said Reagan called him on Thursday, his birthday.
Saturday was the birthdate of Pepper's late wife, Mildred.
   ``I told him we need to have more old folks at the head of
things. He laughed and said he agreed,'' Pepper said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sting, Bruce Springsteen and other
artists drew a sell-out crowd to an Amnesty International global
rock tour concert to promote the defense of human rights.
   More than 90,000 fans crowded this northeastern city's Camp Nou
Stadium on Saturday to see Springsteen and fellow American folk
singer Tracey Chapman perform along with Sting, Peter Gabriel and
Senegal's Youssou N'dour.
   From a wide stage surrounded by a turquoise and green global map
emblazoned with ``Universal Declaration of Human Rights,'' the
stars played their best-known songs as the crowd clapped and sang
in unison.
   One poster seen waving bore the tour's slogan, ``Human Rights,
Now!''
   The concert formed part of the 20-city tour across five
continents marking the 40th anniversary of the United Nations
Universal Declaration on Human Rights.
   Sting told reporters Friday: ``In all the countries we visit,
including my own, there are violations of human rights. No one is
innocent.''
