<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Strike     09-11 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Strike,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Confronts Unions, National Strike Set for Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unions vowed Sunday to shut down
the capital and Argentina's main cities to protest the government's
use of force to break up an anti-government rally.
   The strike, which will affect schools, banks, public
transportation and government offices, is set for Monday.
   The labor unions said the walkout was in response to a police
break-up of a rally on Friday that was part of a national strike to
protest President Raul Alfonsin's economic reforms.
   Thirty-seven police officers were among the 113 people injured
when police used tear gas, rubber bullets and water cannon to
disperse a crowd of 20,000 union members.
   ``The unusual and ferocious attack, unacceptable in a democracy,
was perpetrated by forces of repression more interested in beating
innocent demonstrators than guaranteeing the security of people and
property,'' the General Labor Confederation said Sunday.
   Teachers, bank clerks, bus drivers, construction workers, public
employees and other groups in the capital, Buenos Aires, and in the
cities of Cordoba, Rosario and Mar del Plata said they would stay
off their jobs in support of the strike.
   The strike also has been endorsed by the center-left Peronist
Party and leftist Communist, Socialist, Intransigent and Christian
Democrat parties.
   Alfonsin said in a statement that his government would guarantee
the ``security of the services of public transport throughout the
country.''
   The president's center-right Radical Civic Union says security
forces intervened in Friday's rally to stop fighting and vandalism
that already had broken out.
   Alfonsin's program of economic reforms are aimed at curbing
inflation that has soared to 440 percent in the past year and a 14
percent unemployment rate. Personal incomes have declined for three
straight years.
   The unions contend the anti-inflation plan Alfonsin introduced
in August does not allow wages to keep pace with cost-of-living
increases and that the government must resort to repression to
support an economic program that is unpopular.
   The 3.5 million union members also oppose Alfonsin's efforts to
sell off inefficient state industries, which employ tens of
thousands of union members.
</TEXT>
