<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires-ParkSupt     09-11 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Park Supt,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Superintendent Defends Firefighting Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yellowstone National Park
Superintendent Bob Barbee says critics of the park's fire policy
who blame the policy for major forest fires are directing a
``lynch-mob, hang-him mentality'' at him.
   Critics have ``an hysteric view that the area is on fire because
of a misguided fire policy,'' he said in an interview Saturday.
``Such a view, that the entire American West is on fire because of
a fire policy, is ridiculous.''
   Barbee was disputing recent comments by firefighters and
residents of park gateway communities that the Yellowstone fires
could have been put out early if he had let firefighters use heavy
equipment such as bulldozers and chain saws.
   The national park fire management policy calls for minimal use
of motorized and heavy equipment.
   Barbee said he ``absolutely feels fine'' that Interior Secretary
Donald Hodel supported Yellowstone's fire management practices
during his tour of the fires Saturday.
   But Hodel said Sunday in Boise, Idaho, that the Park Service's
16-year-old ``let burn'' policy didn't work under this year's
extremely dry conditions.
   ``The old policy has to be reviewed and altered,'' Hodel said at
the Boise Interagency Fire Center, which coordinates fire
suppression throughout the country. ``Nobody who has seen it
operate this year could say it was a success.''
   During the 16 years, 16,000 fires burned a total of about 30,000
acres in the park, Hodel said. But currently, nearly 900,000 acres
of Yellowstone's 2.2 million acres are involved in flame.
   ``We'll see a new policy in place before the beginning of the
next fire year,'' he said. Until then, each new fire will be
suppressed with all the equipment and manpower available.
   Barbee said he and other firefighting professionals ``have
nothing to apologize for.''
   ``The very idea staggers me that people boo the efforts made to
control the fires,'' he said. ``The best firefighting technology in
the world is being used here.''
   Barbee said he is ``sorry that people cannot accept the fact
that conditions are so extreme'' and make firefighting difficult.
   Tourism will not decline in Yellowstone because of the fires,
Barbee insisted. He said people will continue to visit the park to
see the thermal features such as the geysers and the wildlife.
   Barbee said that in the past the park has not purposely lit
fires to get rid of dead lodgepole pines that have helped fuel the
fires because it isn't a practical method to get rid of dead trees.
   Under normal weather conditions, lodgepole pines, which covered
80 percent of the park before the fires, ``do not burn quickly and
easily,'' he said. And Yellowstone's rugged terrain does not make
it easy to control planned burns, he added.
   Anyone who thinks planned burns would have prevented the present
fire problems, he said, is ``chewing lotus seeds.''
</TEXT>
