<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Between 60 percent and 70 percent of Pat Walsh's
body is covered with tattoos.
   ``I'm what you'd call a tattooed lady,'' said Ms. Walsh, 40, who
has a jungle panorama of parrots and waterfalls permanently etched
into her back.
   She was among several hundred tattooed men and women, their
admirers and the curious who met at Coney Island Saturday for the
Tattoo Festival.
   ``I've just completed my right leg, an underwater scene
consisting of jellyfish and many lush things from my hip right on
down to my foot,'' the auto-parts store worker from Clifton, N.J.,
said.
   The colorful drawings that now cover much of Ms. Walsh's body
began with one small tattoo six years ago and is now ``my
magnificent obsession,'' she said.
   Her tattoos fulfill a ``desire to make my skin more beautiful
than it was. I cover my skin with birds, flowers, beautiful things
to look at.''
   Shotsie Gorman, a tattoo artist from Haledon, N.J., said the
designs are ``an exciting way of expression.''
   ``Some people collect photos of tattoos, but it's much more
exciting to collect them on your body,'' he said. ``And it's
certainly much more of a commitment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Puppies will be puppies, and puppies
like to swallow things. But $3.42? In small change?
   Baby, a 14-pound American bull terrier who had to have 10 ounces
of junk surgically removed from her stomach, swallowed seven
quarters, seven dimes, seven nickels and 62 pennies. She also
consumed four washers, a nail more than an inch long, a house key
on a key ring, a game token from a pizza parlor, a small piece of
electrical wire and some pellets from a shotgun shell.
   Kelli Brown noticed Baby was acting a little sluggish and took
her to Dr. Phillip L. Curry, who told her an X-ray of the dog's
stomach showed a ``huge blob.''
   Curry said that during the operation he and his staff ``just
kept hunting and we just kept finding things.''
   Curry said he has seen animals eat everything from small balls
and jacks to needles and as much as five pounds of rocks.
   ``It's not unusual to have them swallow things,'' Curry said.
``But this is unusual from the standpoint of the size of the dog
and the volume (consumed).''
   Baby was to go home Monday or Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Shakespeare once suggested killing all the
lawyers as a way to rid society of squabbling and avarice.
   Lawyer Bill Berger and artist Ricardo Martinez have some rather
irreverent suggestions on how to dispose of the bodies.
   Their book, ``What to do With a Dead Lawyer'' is a compilation
of drawings offering various scenarios to that end.
   ``The legal profession is inclined to take itself too
seriously,'' said Berger. ``No one is above being satirized.
   ``I thought the idea of doing horrible things to lawyers was
quite funny,'' Berger said.
   ``The more we went along, it seems the nastier we became,''
added Martinez.
   The drawings include a shredded corporate lawyer as part of a
ticker-tape parade, a management lawyer who becomes a time-card
punch for hard-hat construction workers and a tobacco company's
lawyer who becomes an ashtray.
   ``It's good for someone like an attorney to poke fun at
themselves,'' said Berger, 39.
   Berger and Martinez have sold about 500 books so far.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTWOOD, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All the activity was in the stands at
the Brightwood Tavern's sixth annual slug races.
   The spectators were whipped into a frenzy. Trainers, owners and
fans yelled, screamed and booed. But the racers, well, you might
say they were sluggish.
   Slick, Slither and Sturgeon Lips were among the 55 contestants
in Saturday's race.
   They were weighed and measured, and then the action started. If
you could call it action.
   The slugs were placed in the center of a circle drawn on a large
board. At the end of two minutes, the winner was the one who has
traveled the farthest.
   The crowd roared when tavern owner Bob Swarts yelled, ``They're
off!''
   Nothing happened.
   The four slugs in the first race just sat there. Three looked as
if they were asleep. Sturgeon Lips looked bored.
   Finally, it squirmed a few times and waved its antennae around.
It moved a few inches and stopped.
   The winner was a slug named Dorsey III.
</TEXT>
