<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Over Yellowstone, Yellowstone Smoke Over New York State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light snow fell Sunday over the northern Rockies, remnants of
hurricane Florence produced more heavy rain in the South and
showers were scattered across the Plains and Southeast.
   Light snow fell over sections of Montana and western Wyoming,
with almost 2 inches of snow in Wyoming at Burgess Junction and the
northern part of Grand Teton National Park. An inch fell at Mammoth
Hot Springs, at the northern entrance of Yellowstone National Park.
   Smoke from the forest fires in and around Yellowstone has
gradually spread eastward and was over Pennsylvania and New York
state Sunday. It was carried by westerly wind at an altitude of
15,000 to 20,000 feet.
   The smoke gave a hazy appearance to the sky and may cause
colorful sunrises and sunsets, the National Weather Service said.
   The leftovers of Florence spread locally heavy rain across
Louisiana, with 1 to 3 inches over north-central and northeastern
sections of the state. The heaviest rainfall reported was 3.06
inches at Jonesboro, with 2.84 inches at Vixian.
   Other showers and thunderstorms developed along a cold front
over the eastern half of the Dakotas, southeastern Wyoming,
Colorado and New Mexico.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed over Florida, Georgia,
South Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Mississippi and Arkansas.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.10 inches of rain fell
Tyndall Air Force Base at Panama City, Fla.
   Hurricane Gilbert was east of Jamaica with highest sustained
wind of 100 and was moving west across the Caribbean.
   Afternoon temperatures were only in the 30s and 40s over western
North Dakota and the northern Rockies.
   Astoria, Ore., had a record low of 37; Olympia, Wash., had a
record low of 34; and Corpus Christi, Texas, tied its record low of
67.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Yellowstone National Park to 101 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Sunday morning's low was 22 degrees at Jackson, Wyo., south of
Yellowstone.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over eastern sections of the lower and middle Mississippi Valley,
the Tennessee Valley and the lower Ohio Valley. Scattered showers
and a few thunderstorms were forecast ahead of and along a cold
front over the upper Great Lakes, southern sections of the upper
Mississippi Valley, South Dakota, Nebraska and sections of the
central and southern Rockies.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted over most of the northern Plains
and northern Rockies; in the 60s over sections of the northern and
central intermountain region between the Sierra Nevada and the
Rockies, from northeastern Colorado across central Nebraska to
northeastern Minnesota, and over northern New England; in the 90s
over Florida, the Gulf Coast region, the lower Mississippi Valley,
the southern Plains, eastern Kansas and the inland valleys of
California; near 100 over the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and
80s over the remainder of the country.
</TEXT>
