<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acid, Knives Used In Attacks On Alleged Collaborators</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with more wounded, New Year's
detail; picks up 11th pvs: `I think...'
^By KARIN LAUB</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian activists stabbed and seriously
wounded an Arab physician Sunday and the army said attackers threw
acid in the faces of two other Arab doctors who allegedly
collaborated with Israeli authorities.
   Israeli officials voiced concern about the surge of attacks in
which four suspected collaborators were killed in the past week.
   ``We are monitoring the situation very carefully because in this
phase, Palestinian violence has increasingly turned against
Palestinians,'' said Col. Raanan Gissin, an army spokesman.
   Israelis prayed in synagogues and enjoyed picnics in celebration
of the Jewish New Year, Rosh Hashana, that began Sunday. Police and
military units were reinforced for the holiday as violence
continued in the nine-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   One of Haifa's chief rabbis, Shaar Yashuv Cohen, ruled that
worshipers can carry handguns into synagogues if they are
concealed, Israel radio reported.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, in a message to the armed
forces, said the coming year ``did not promise peace and quiet.''
   Hospital officials said 13 Palestinians were wounded Sunday in
clashes with Israeli troops in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. They
said eight were wounded by army gunfire in Gaza's Shati refugee
camp and the five others were wounded in and around the West Bank
city of Nablus.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In response to the latest attacks on Arabs suspected of
collaborating with Israel, six members of the Israeli-appointed
municipal council in the West Bank village of Yatta resigned,
saying they feared for their lives. The seventh council member,
Mayor Ismail Abu Hemeid, remained in his post.
   ``We saw what happened to people who didn't obey the orders of
the uprising leaders,'' council member Khalil Abu Sabha said. Two
weeks ago, a suspected collaborator was hacked to death in Yatta.
   The latest leaflet from the pro-PLO United National Leadership
of the Uprising called on Palestinians to ``rid ourselves of
collaborators and go after those who have not resigned from their
jobs with the Israeli government.''
   Meanwhile, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud
Bloc called on Arab states to form a Palestinian negotiating team
not connected with the Palestine Liberation Organization for Middle
East peace talks.
   ``I think it's possible with the assistance of neighboring Arab
countries, which by a joint effort can succeed in establishing an
authorized and convincing (Palestinian) representation,'' he said.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, the Labor Party leader, was
quoted by the daily Yediot Ahronot as saying the PLO probably would
win recognition from the United States if it renounced terror and
accepted Israel's right to exist.
   But he declined to specify if Israel would then talk to the PLO,
saying he was ``not ready to give an answer that would amount to
giving credibility.''
   In the northern West Bank town of Jenin, an assailant ambushed
the head of the local health department, Dr. Ahmed Nayef Istaiteh,
outside his office and stabbed him in the chest, stomach and right
arm, Jenin hospital officials said.
   Istaiteh, 45, was transferred to Afula Hospital in northern
Israel and was reported in serious condition. The attacker was
captured, Israel radio said.
   Istaiteh apparently was targeted because he worked for the West
Bank military government. He also carried a weapon, a sign that he
cooperated with Israeli authorities.
   In the Gaza Strip, masked assailants Saturday threw acid at two
Arab doctors from Nasser Hospital in Khan Yunis and the victims
suffered eye and face injuries.
   Israel radio they were singled out for allegedly providing the
army with information about patients hurt in clashes with troops.
   A military official acknowledged that the army could not prevent
all attacks.
   ``We try to assist them as much as we can, but the
responsibility is theirs,'' said the official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Four suspected collaborators have been killed in the past week.
The latest fatality was reported Sunday by the Jerusalem Post,
which said the body of Issa Yasin, 30, a suspected collaborator,
was found in the village Anin near Jenin over the weekend.
   The other victims were a Moslem official from Jaffa who
reportedly sold land to Israelis, a member of an underground
``popular committee'' accused of being an informer and a
26-year-old man who allegedly cooperated with Israeli security.
   The latest fatalities brought to 264 the number of Palestinians
killed in the uprising. Most have been killed by Israeli gunfire,
but the figure includes those killed by Palestinians.
   Six Israelis, including Rachel Weiss, an elderly woman found
dead near her collective farm in the Negev Aug. 3, have also been
killed.
</TEXT>
