<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Politics     09-11 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Politics,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Seeks To Head Off No-Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi came under
attack by opposition leaders Sunday and warned the parliament that
a vote of no-confidence in his new government will hamper Iran's
post-war recovery.
   ``For the sake of the country ... we must all try to be
flexible,'' said Musavi, addressing the 270-member Majlis, or
parliament, before it began discussing his 21-man Cabinet,
according to Tehran Radio.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said four members of the
opposition criticized the new government while five representatives
praised it.
   The official Islamic Republic news agency said the confidence
vote, set earlier for Sunday, would be postponed a day.
   The IRNA report said the Majlis will ``listen to remarks of the
government's representative in defense of the Cabinet ministers
before casting their votes for or against the Cabinet.''
   Divisions that have plagued the Iranian leadership for years
sharpened after Tehran's abrupt July 18 acceptance of the U.N.
Security Council's cease-fire resolution in the 8-year-old war with
Iraq. Iran agreed to the cease-fire after a string of military
defeats.
   Diplomatic sources said Musavi opposed the cease-fire, which
began Aug. 20. The acceptance was believed to have been
masterminded by Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of the parliament and
Iran's military commander, the second most powerful figure in Iran
after Khomeini.
   The parliamentary debate Sunday was on the government Musavi
announced in July after parliamentary elections in April and May.
   IRNA said the debate focused on the ministries of the Interior,
the Islamic Revolution's Guards Corps, Agriculture, Labor and
Social Affairs as well as Post Telegraph and Telephones.
   The prime minister warned if his ministers do not win a vote of
confidence ``their offices will remain virtually vacant'' until
presidential elections scheduled for next year.
   Musavi, 46, submitted his resignation to President Ali Khamenei
on Monday, claiming that as many as eight of his ministers faced
no-confidence votes in parliament.
   He retracted his resignation Tuesday night after Khamenei
rejected it and Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini publicly rebuked him
for making the surprise move at such a critical juncture while Iran
was negotiating a peace settlement with Iraq.
   Musavi, a radical who favors tight state control of the economy,
opposes bringing in foreign companies to help Iran rebuild. He has
warned that would drive Iran, its economy bled dry by the war, deep
into debt.
   He is opposed by Khamenei, who has close links with the merchant
class and conservative clerics, and Rafsanjani, the leading
advocate of ending Iran's isolation by improving links with the
West.
   Some Western economists estimate reconstruction will cost Iran
around $40 billion. Iran has foreign reserves estimated at $5
billion, but owes around 2 billion dollars.
   Iran, like Iraq, is expected to boost its oil production,
currently restricted by an Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, to pay its reconstruction bill. But that would drive oil
prices down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
