<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DelawarePrimary     09-11 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Primary,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beard Defeats Woo, Begins Senate Race Against Roth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With an upset primary victory behind him,
wealthy civic activist Samuel S. Beard began campaigning Sunday for
a U.S. Senate race against Republican incumbent William V. Roth Jr.
   Beard, 49, was the underdog in a Democratic primary Saturday
that pitted him against heavily financed Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo, 51.
Roth did not have a primary opponent.
   Campaign finance reports filed in late August showed Woo having
raised $407,998, Beard with $65,008 and Roth with $734,933.
   Several small precincts did not plan to report voting results
until Monday, but with 97 percent of the vote counted, Beard had
22,418, or 53 percent, to Woo's 19,624, or 47 percent.
   A little over 30 percent of the 133,386 Democrats eligible to
vote turned out.
   New Castle County, which includes Wilmington, helped push Beard
over the top, as he won his home county with 17,001 to Woo's 13,296.
   Beard, who inherited his wealth, had the support of party
loyalists and unions. Woo, of Newark, was a champion of
Asian-Americans nationwide and had the support of the college set.
   Woo said in a statement after his electoral defeat, ``I always
said it was a tough way to earn a living,'' adding he looked
forward to returning to teaching physics at the University of
Delaware.
   The native of Shanghai, China, gave up the right to run for
re-election as lieutenant governor to make the run for the Senate.
   Beard said Saturday that his campaign for the November election
would begin Sunday morning.
   ``I'm going to start going out and thanking the people who
helped support this campaign and then start putting our plans
together for the fall,'' he said.
   Beard attributed his victory to a ``grassroots, issue-oriented
approach.'' Among issues he said voters agreed with him on was
foreign investment, which he said Woo ``was prepared to encourage.''
   ``I've spent all my life creating jobs here, building industry.
We need to increase our exports. I do not encourage foreign
investors purchasing our farms or our businesses,'' Beard said.
   ``We ran a campaign on broad issues. S.B. focused mostly on
technology,'' he said.
   Woo had contended that there was a need for scientists in the
Senate to be able to competently discuss issues dealing with
technology.
   In the final week of the campaign, it was disclosed that Woo's
ethnic background had become a target.
   A letter supporting Beard and written by Edward ``Pete''
Peterson, president of the Delaware AFL-CIO, called on supporters
to ``save this country ... from Asian influences the lieutenant
governor refers to'' as well as ``all foreign influence.''
   Peterson wrote another letter last week, apologizing to anyone
who might have been offended by the statement.
   Peterson said he was referring to Woo's claims of contacts with
many business leaders in Asia.
</TEXT>
