<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     09-11 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugees Say They Suffer From Poison Gas Allegedly Used By Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kurdish refugees at a camp near this
eastern city cited a litany of ailments they said they suffered
when the Iraqi army drove them from their villages with poison gas.
   ``My whole body itches, one of my eyes is blinded, I have
trouble breathing,'' Iskender Omer, 58, said Sunday.
   He said he and other refugees left the town of Zahor in northern
Iraq 20 days ago when Iraqi planes began dropping chemical bombs on
their village.
   ``They made very little noise, these bombs, a yellow smoke
emanated from them and a foul, garlic-like smell was in the air,''
he told The Associated Press from his bed in one the 500 tents set
up to house the refugees.
   Mustard gas is distinguishable by its garlic-like smell.
   He and his 30-year-old son Halil Iskender said many people from
their village died because they were closer to where the bombs
fell. The two said they saved themselved by throwing themselves
into an irrigation canal.
   The United States has accused Iraq of using chemical weapons
against its Kurdish minority. The U.S. Senate on Friday approved
economic sanctions against Iraq.
   Turkey, which has given sanctuary to about 60,000 Kurds fleeing
the Iraqi attacks, said Friday no evidence of chemical weapons use
was found in screening the sick and injured among the refugees.
   The Turkish government set up a clinic with 10 doctors and 25
nurses in the camp, which houses 8,000 refugees.
   Doctors say they have not determined that any of the deaths
among the refugees or the symptoms of illnesses among the refugees
were caused by poison gas.
   ``These people have been on the road for days, they suffer from
exhaustion and various infections, including eye infections,'' said
Dr. Sinan Seyfioglu.
   Seyfioglu believes their findings from the refugees neither
confirm or deny the use of chemical weapons.
   ``This does not mean Iraq did not use poison gas. But if these
people had been exposed, I don't believe they could make it over
here,'' he said.
   But Kurdish guerrillas in the camp near Diyarbakir said they
would still be in Iraq fighting if they did not have to escape from
chemical bomb attacks.
   They showed a 3{-year-old boy, Isa Ismail, and said scabs
covering his entire face are the result of poison gas.
   ``Where we come from, birds no longer fly, even the animals are
dead,'' said Cemal Salih, wearing the baggy brown pants which is
the uniform of the Peshmergas, the Kurdish guerrillas.
   ``We ran without burying our dead,'' he said. He said, along
with others, that he was willing to go back and show the dead
bodies to observers if it were possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
