<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Slaying     09-11 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Slaying,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Mayoral Candidate Gunned Down In Veracruz State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen in a stolen taxi killed an opposition
mayoral candidate outside his house in a small town in Veracruz
state as his wife looked on, police said Sunday.
   Inocencio Romero Juarez, the Mexican Socialist Party mayoral
candidate in Tezonapa, died from four gunshot wounds at about 8
p.m. Saturday night, said Jazinto Licona, a Federal Judicial Police
supervisor in Veracruz.
   Licona said the candidate was standing at the door of his house,
talking to his wife, Maria Lucia, when shots were fired from a
passing taxi. He said Mrs. Romero Juarez told police several people
were in the cab.
   Tezonapa is a town of about 7,000 people about 50 miles from the
Gulf of Mexico port of Veracruz, the state capital 190 miles east
of Mexico City. Licona spoke in a telephone interview.
   Gilberto Rincon Gallardo, national leader of the Mexican
Socialist Party, told the liberal Mexico City daily La Jornada that
the shooting appeared to be politically motivated.
   His party belongs to a democratic reform coalition headed by
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who finished second in the July presidential
elections won by Carlos Salinas de Gortari of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI). Cardenas' coalition has targeted Oct. 2
municipal elections in Veracruz in their campaign to end the
governing party's 59-year domination of Mexican politics.
   Police rejected any political motive in Romero Juarez' death.
   ``Inocencio Romero Juarez was a person dedicated to business ..
. a tranquil person. This could not have been something
political,'' Francisco Torral, a state police spokesman in Veracruz
said in a telephone interview.
   Torral said the taxi was stolen shortly before the shooting of
Romero Juarez. Police had no exact age for Juarez, but said he was
45 or 46.
   The Cardenas movement maintains that six earlier shootings in
Mexico City, including the slaying of a Cardenas advisor a few days
before the July 6 presidential election, are political.
   Authorities have rejected politics as a motive in each case,
none of which has been solved.
</TEXT>
