<HEAD>Talks Back In Low Gear After Direct Meeting Breaks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stalled Iran-Iraq peace talks suffered another
setback Sunday after a meeting between the two foreign ministers
and the U.N. mediator.
   U.N. officials were known to be trying to reconvene the
ministers to move the talks along, but attempts to call a meeting
Sunday were abandoned by late evening. Consultations took place
throughout the day, U.N. spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said.
   Whether to shift the talks to New York appears to be the latest
obstacle to finding a permanent peace after a U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war began Aug. 20. The
United Nations and Iran are believed to favor the shift of venue
while Iraq has publicly opposed it.
   The U.N. mediator, Jan Eliasson, appeared to be waiting for
signs of compromise from either side. Efforts to break the deadlock
were due to continue Monday.
   On Saturday, the two foreign ministers met with Eliasson for 3{
hours in their first face-to-face talks since the second day of the
negotiations Aug. 26. The exchanges between the two parties has
otherwise been indirect.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar personally
mediated the first week of talks, then appointed Eliasson as his
representative.
   The negotiations have been stalled since the start after Iraq
demanded early discussion of free navigation and clearing of its
main sea outlet, the Shatt al-Arab waterway, and Iran refused.
