<HEAD>Famed Family Therapist Dead of Cancer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs final graf to CORRECT year to 1936 sted 1963.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia M. Satir, known in the
medical profession as a pioneer of family therapy, died Saturday of
pancreatic cancer. She was 72.
   Satir was known around the world for the techniques she
developed for treating troubled families.
   Her works on family therapy include ``Conjoint Family Therapy,''
published in 1964, ``Self-Esteem,'' ``Helping Families To Change''
and ``Meditations and Inspirations.''
   Satir helped found the Mental Research Institute in Palo Alto in
1959 and founded the International Human Learning Resource Network
20 years later.
   Satir received her bachelor's degree in 1936 from the University
of Wisconsin and earned several graduate degrees, including a
master's degree from the University of Chicago in 1948.
