<DOCNO> AP880911-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaddResigns     09-11 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ladd Resigns,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alan Ladd Jr. Resigns as Chairman of MGM Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Ladd Jr., who nurtured the hit
films ``Moonstruck'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' has resigned as
chairman and chief executive officer of MGM Pictures Inc., the
studio announced Sunday.
   Ladd, 50, a former president of 20th Century Fox and president
of The Ladd Co., also resigned as director of MGM-UA Communications
Co.
   ``Over the past few months, I had received inquiries from third
parties regarding other opportunities; I felt that it was
inappropriate for me to consider these while still affiliated with
MGM,'' Ladd said in a studio-prepared statement. ``Recently, I made
the decision to pursue other interests.''
   The statement did not disclose details of the opportunities.
   Ladd said the recent releases ``Moonstruck,'' which won Academy
Awards for actresses Cher and Olympia Dukakis, ``Willow,'' and ``A
Fish Called Wanda'' leave MGM ``in the best shape its has been in
the past several years.''
   The company also recently released ``Betrayed,'' a film about
white supremacy in America's heartland.
   MGM-UA Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Stephen D. Silbert
said Ladd was responsible for numerous successful projects.
   ``We regret his departure,'' Silbert said.
   While at 20th Century Fox, Ladd, son of the late actor Alan
Ladd, was responsible for such hits as ``Star Wars'' and ``The
Omen.'' Among his other successes are ``Chariots of Fire'' and
``Police Academy.''
   Ladd's resignation follows that of MGM-UA Communications Co.
Chairman Lee Rich in July. Earler this month, Rich and Warner Bros.
announced a long-term agreement to produce movie and television
projects.
   A plan earlier this summer to split MGM-UA Communications into
two separate companies collapsed as financiers Kirk Kerkorian and
Burt Sugarman announced they were unable to agree on details of the
$400 million deal.
   MGM-UA reported in July the company lost $8.3 million or 16
cents a share in its third quarter, an improvement over the loss of
$27.5 million, or 55 cents a share in the comparable period a year
earlier. Revenue for the quarter ended May 31 was $175.2 million,
up from $72.4 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
