<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 2214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti 3rdLd-Writethru   09-11 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0521,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Stage Massacre During Church Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf with five grafs to UPDATE with protest called
for Sunday, streets deserted, quote from former candidate; picks up
7th pvs: The journalist...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Men armed with guns and machetes
burst into the church of a militant Roman Catholic priest Sunday
and killed at least three parishioners, wounded 60 and burned down
the building, witnesses and news reports said.
   Police stood near the church but none came to the rescue,
witnesses said. After the attack, gangs of men roamed the deserted
streets and stoned the offices of two groups opposed to the
military regime of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy.
   The Rev. Jean-Bertrand Aristide, an outspoken opponent of the
military government, had just begun a 9 a.m. (9 a.m. EDT) Mass when
a group of men began throwing rocks at the church, panicking
hundreds inside who rushed for the doors, said a foreign journalist
attending the service.
   ``Suddenly the doors at the back of the church burst open and 20
to 30 men with machetes, huge sticks and guns came in. They were
dressed in civilian clothes,'' said the journalist, who contacted
The Associated Press in New York by telephone.
   ``They started shooting people, beating them, and stabbing and
slashing them,'' the reporter said. ``They stabbed a woman who was
pregnant. They stabbed another man who ran outside the church. He
died. Some people were shot.''
   Estimates of the numbers of parishioners in the church, inside a
compound ringed by a wall, ranged from 600 to 1,500.
   Frightened residents fled to their homes after the attacks and
only the bands of men remained on the streets. The attack came on a
day when opposition groups had planned a a protest of Namphy's
voiding of the constitution in July.
   A Crusade for the Constitution Committee, headed by the
political opposition, had urged Haitians to dress in white Sunday
in a show of protest. Few people could be seen wearing white in the
city, however.
   Paul Latortue, a former senate candidate in Haiti, said he was
sure the church attack was the work of the government and its
supporters.
   ``They've wanted to kill Aristide for a long time,'' he said in
San Juan, where he teaches economics at the University of Puerto
Rico. ``It is significant that the government tried to do this
today, a day of protest.''
   The journalist, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at
least three parishioners were killed. Parishioners surrounded and
protected Aristide, who was uninjured.
   Radio Haiti-Inter reported 60 people suffering from gunshot
wounds and machete slashes were being treated at the public general
hospital.
   Dr. Roger Valme, assistant director of the hospital where bodies
are normally taken, refused comment on the casualties.
   One witness said ``I saw a pregnant woman with a bullet hole in
her belly.''
   Firefighters responded around 10 a.m., but the fire gutted the
modest cement-block church and the roof collapsed before the blaze
was extinguished.
   Radio-Inter reported the attackers were dressed in civilian
clothes and wearing red armbands.
   Bands of men roamed the streets of the city after the attack,
and shortly after 3 p.m. stoned the headquarters of two opposition
political parties and Radio Cacique, a populist and outspoken
station.
   The unidentified men attacked the headquarters of Louis Dejoie's
National Agriculture and Industry Party and of Sylvio Claude's
Christian Democratic Party.
   Aristide is one of the most popular opposition leaders in Haiti.
There have been several attempts on his life blamed on forces loyal
to the government.
   Namphy returned to power in a coup June 19 after four months of
civilian rule under President Leslie Manigat. Namphy ruled for two
years as head of a junta after Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile
in France on Feb. 7, 1986.
   The journalist said she was told that many more than three
people were killed inside the church, but the bodies couldn't be
removed before the attackers set the building on fire and torched
cars parked out in front.
   ``One parishioner grabbed me and used me as a shield,'' she
said. ``I had to hit him to release me because I couldn't get out
of the church. I tried to run down the main aisle and that's when I
ran into one of the thugs with a knife.
   ``He grabbed me and ripped my dress, but I got away.''
   The church has a main back door, where the gunmen rushed in, and
two smaller side doors, she said.
   ``People fled from side doors in the crush,'' the journalist
said. ``There was a terrible panic and stampede.
   ``Parishioners tried to climb over the walls into the street,
but men with batons stopped them. The men then surrounded the
church building and set it on fire.''
   She said no one came to the rescue during the attack, despite
the presence of a military compound across the street. Soldiers
standing outside the church compound watched, but did not help, she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880911-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GangViolence     09-11 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alleged Victims Testify of Police Misconduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are using the fight against gang
violence to legitimize abuse of people's civil rights, an NAACP
official said.
   ``Under the guise of the gang crisis in our community, innocent
people are being harassed and rights are being infringed upon. We
are desperate to correct that,'' said Anthony Essex, local chapter
president of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People.
   Essex spoke Saturday at an NAACP-sponsored hearing on
allegations of police misconduct.
   ``We shouldn't have to be concerned about the fact that when we
call for protection, we have to be subjected to the same
degradation inflicted on common criminals,'' Essex said.
   Alicia Jones, one of a half-dozen people who spoke at the
hearing, said she found herself on the floor with a gun pointed at
her head one night when she answered a knock at her door.
   She was held down by a Los Angeles County sheriff's deputy while
six other officers searched her apartment for cocaine, she said.
When no drugs were found and she had been questioned, she said, the
deputies realized the vehicles they had been watching actually
belonged to someone next door.
   ``I just couldn't believe this was happening to me. I felt as if
I was watching this happen to someone else,'' she said. ``I don't
bother anybody. I don't use drugs or associate with people who do.
I don't even like to drink.''
   Cmdr. William Booth, spokesman for the Police Department, said
the police have support from the general community.
   ``It wasn't that long ago that the community was demanding more
police officers to do something about rising gang violence,'' he
said. ``And the community is safer than it was before we started
saturating the community with police officers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
