<HEAD>Strikes Cutting Into School Time In Six States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 students in six states were expected to have
classes disrupted Monday by strikes involving more than 6,100
teachers in 23 districts.
   In Peabody, Mass., school officials and representatives of 400
striking teachers were back at the bargaining table Sunday trying
to keep public school classes from being canceled a fourth day.
   The state Labor Relations Commission has outlawed the strike,
and school officials have mailed letters threatening to fire the
teachers after a hearing procedure, said Mayor Peter Torigan.
   A spokeswoman for the teachers dismissed the notices as a
pressure tactic and said the strike would continue.
   Pay is at the heart of the Peabody dispute, and many of the
others in Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   In Peabody, teachers are seeking a three-year contract with a 9
percent pay increase each year. David Whitmore, a spokesman for the
Peabody Federation of Teachers, said the town proposed a 5.5
percent increase for each of the next three years.
   The Peabody strike affects about 5,700 students. A strike in
Illinois' Granite City district is disrupting classes for about
8,200 students. Michigan and Pennsylvania each have strikes in 9
districts, involving more than 40,000 students in each state.
Strikes in Ohio affect about 4,250 students and in New Jersey about
1,450 students.
