<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to abortion, George Bush and
Michael Dukakis agree on one thing: each man says he personally
does not favor the controversial procedure.
   But beyond their personal feelings, the Republican and
Democratic presidential nominees have staked out opposite stands on
whether abortion should be legal and whether the government should
pay for the operation for poor women.
   Bush favors a constitutional amendment to overturn the 1973
Supreme Court decision, Roe vs. Wade, that legalized abortion. He
favors outlawing all abortions except in cases of rape, incest or
to save the life of the mother. He opposes Medicaid funding of
abortions for poor women except to save the woman's life.
   Dukakis, as a legislator and governor of Massachusetts, has been
a resolute supporter of women's legal right to choose abortion, as
well as government-funding of the operation for the poor.
